<TEXT>
mikhail s gorbachev was 19 when he 
saw this city and it was in ruins it was then called stalingrad 
and it had been the scene of one of the bloodiest and most savage 
battles of the second world war 
it left an impression that was still vivid in gorbachevs mind 
more than three and a half decades later 
i went to study at moscow state university and i traveled 
through stalingrad which had been destroyed through voronezh 
which had been destroyed he told an interviewer in 1986 
nothing but ruins everywhere the whole country was in ruins 
world war ii divided gorbachevs family and devastated much of 
his home region in southern russia by the time he saw stalingrad 
in 1950 war for the budding law student was no vague or distant 
concept but a terrible reality that had hit close to home 
today more than four decades after the red army struggled and 
defeated the invading nazi armies the war continues to haunt the 
collective soviet soul and perhaps gorbachev himself 
for soviets the conflict they call the great patriotic war 
is simultaneously a glorious chapter in their countrys history 
proof of the superiority of socialism a convenient alibi when 
things go wrong and a tragedy whose scars are felt even today 
the wartime alliance between the united states and soviet union 
against the axis is also cited by gorbachev chief of the communist 
party as proof that the superpowers need not be adversaries but 
can be allies 
when the time posed the question acutely irrevocably and that 
question had to be answered the soviet and american peoples 
united he told a group of american schoolchildren who visited 
the kremlin earlier this month the present time also makes 
vast demands above all on our two great peoples 
virtually every soviet family including gorbachevs was 
touched by the four years of bitter fighting that ranged throughout 
the western soviet union and claimed the lives of 20 million soviet 
soldiers and civilians 
after the german armies drove across the soviet border in june 
1941 gorbachevs father sergei a tractor driver was called to 
the front and served for four years mikhail was 10 years old when 
the fighting broke out 
his native stavropol region 300 miles southwest of volgograd 
was overrun by the german 40th panzer corps for seven months 
beginning in august 1942 just as the battle for stalingrad was 
raging 
from just one collective farm in the stavropol region in the 
village of beshpagir 417 young men and women went away to fight 
and were killed in battle 
the grip of world war ii on the soviet mind and the use made of 
the memories by authorities are nowhere more evident than in the 
city once called stalingrad in the titanic battle that raged here 
as many as 1 million soviets may have perished and 15 million 
germans were killed wounded or taken prisoner 
in this city situated on a bend in the volga river 600 miles 
south of moscow 90 percent of the buildings in the industrial and 
residential center were devastated by artillery strikes dive 
bombing raids and months of dogged housetohouse fighting 
president franklin d roosevelt said the eightmonth battle that 
ended in february 1943 with the surrender of encircled nazi units 
had marked the turning point in the war of the allied nations 
against the forces of aggression 
at former soviet battlefield sites like volgograd every day is 
memorial day about 3 million soviets visit a gigantic memorial 
complex here each year many of them veterans returning to see the 
place where many of their comrades were killed 
you feel a great weight in your soul said amazas s 
arutunyan 63 an armenian who served as a private in the 93rd 
artillery regiment until he was badly wounded so many men fell 
in combat some screaming others just falling in silence like 
leaves 
the war medals worn by the wizened man thumped against his chest 
as he slowly climbed a halfmile to the top of mamayev kurgan hill 
where a huge statue of mother russia slightly larger than the 
statue of liberty brandishes a sword and calls on her children to 
smite the invader 
in a cavernous hall dominated by an enormous white stone hand 
holding a blazing torch 34 dipped red banners record the names of 
more than 7000 soviet men and women who died defending stalingrad 
a recording of solemn music plays over and over 
the effect is overpowering 
you cannot come here without tears said nadezhda denisova 
61 a volgograder who was 19 when the battle of stalingrad began 
her eyes welled there were so many dead 
a visitors book is filled with poignant messages left by those 
who have come to the monument one man wrote uncle vasiya i 
have found you at last your name is on one of the banners 
the memorial complex on mamayev kurgan hill does not only stress 
the heroism and patriotism of the soviets who fought here but also 
the fact that they fought in the name of socialism and soviet power 
the name of josef v stalin wartime generalissimo and soviet 
dictator was stripped from this city in 1961 when it was renamed 
volgograd but now the party as a whole is lauded as the organizer 
of world war ii victory 
olga sobelyova made that point as she slowly escorted a group of 
24 orphans from the central russian city of sasovo up the hill 
toward the giant statue of mother russia 
children you mustnt think that it was just our armies who 
won here said the 41yearold guide from volgograd it was our 
entire country our socialist system and our communist party 
