you fly in on the state airline aeroflot make 
your way through kgb passport and customs control and catch a ride 
downtown with a driver from the state travel monopoly intourist 
gum the huge stateowned department store is packed but not 
because theres a sale on there are no sales the prices are fixed 
by thats right the state 
thats life in the ussr this is after all a communist state 
but less so it seems every day that perestroika survives 
if the buzzword of the 1980s in america has been 
entrepreneurship the key word here is cooperatives 
under the banner of perestroika the gorbachev campaign to 
restructure the nations stagnant economy authorities last week 
acted on new laws that will encourage the expansion of 
cooperatives economic units akin in many ways to the small 
business sector of the united states except that all employees are 
coowners and thus share in the profits 
profits 
profits have come to the soviet union and thus profit motive 
soviet premier nikolai ryzhkov said last week that 14000 
cooperatives were formed in the first 18 months they were 
permitted with another 6000 formed in the past three months the 
cooperative system he said optimistically in a short time can 
solve the most severe problems of perestroika the demand of the 
population for goods and services 
perestroika signals a dramatic evolution in the communist 
economy that has built a huge military might and an ominous 
bureaucracy but little in the way of consumer services that people 
in the west have come to take for granted 
foreigners who live here send out to helsinki for the finer 
things in life when the train from finland arrives at leningrad 
station here it is loaded down with the fruits of the capitalist 
west such as dishwashing detergent modern ranges fresh produce 
and big macs 
soviet citizens have neither the income nor the hard currency 
nor the authority to order out instead they shop in stateowned 
shops where variety is rare and the stock is either overpriced or 
depleted as a rule quality is nothing to brag about either 
perestroika is already in deep trouble not the least because 
economic restructuring has brought the uncertainties of layoffs and 
future price increases without any of the rewards of a true 
consumer economy 
change has been a long time coming to the soviet union the 
local press has come to dismiss the brezhnevtochernenko era 
19641985 as the period of stagnation that said the moscow 
news a statecontrolled paper that takes advantage of glasnost 
the democratic companion of perestroika to push the economic 
reforms on the front page has run reams about cooperatives 
its the hot topic in town at least among the intellectuals and 
the foreign community in new york you ask a cabbie to take you to 
elaines maybe in moscow you ask for a cooperative and if youre 
lucky you make your way to one of the new restaurants owned by 
its employees who pocket the profit and thus have an incentive to 
create an attractive dinner or sew an attractive dress 
for the past six months the way to the vavilova market has 
become lined with wooden stalls and card tables as vendors sell 
whatever they can make or get their hands on one young lady is 
modeling a redandwhite striped apron and has a dozen on the table 
starting at 30 rubles about 50 a fellow across the way has got 
his hands on some stylish western blue jeans for sale he says 
at 130 rubles 200 a months pay for many muscovites 
after dinner walk through the arbat shopping mall or even red 
square and you see artists selling their portraits of st basils 
cathedral or the lenin mausoleum they implore they barter they 
discount they would be capitalists or eccentrics at the 
pontevecchio in florence or in ghirardelli square in san 
francisco but in moscow they call themselves cooperatives 
one new coop restaurant in the northern section of moscow 
displays the stickers of major credit cards familiar in the west 
and tries to make foreigners pay with plastic an open violation of 
currency laws that forbid practically all private trade in hard 
currency 
prices at the restaurant double at midnight and one unwary 
foursome found themselves stuck with a 98ruble 170 bill for 
dinner outrageous by soviet standards but more and more common as 
coops learn the demand is there at practically any price in this 
supplystarved economy 
this turn in the local economy is not without controversy or 
opposition and many are the residents who recall khrushchevera 
reform efforts and expect this goround to goround too the 
current edition of the moscow news has a piece whose frontpage 
teaser says worker demands a revision of the law on state 
enterprise 
the worker identified as steelmaker mikhail koptev complained 
