<TEXT>
dutch police on tuesday recovered 
three paintings including works by vincent van gogh and paul 
cezanne less than two weeks after they were stolen from this 
citys municipal museum police said 
three dutchmen were arrested when they tried to sell the 
19thcentury paintings in an amsterdam hotel said police spokesman 
klaas wilting 
the works whose combined worth has been estimated at up to 52 
million were recovered undamaged he told the associated press 
the art theft was the nations biggest ever 
wilting refused to disclose any further details of the hotel 
transaction 
he would also not say whether the three suspects were thought to 
include the burglars who smashed a museum window and stole the 
three works on may 20 
stolen were carnations a 1888 work by the dutch painter van 
gogh bottle with apples a still life painted in 1894 by the 
french master cezanne and the house of maitre billaud in 
nevers an 1874 painting by dutch artist johan jongkind 
museum director wim beeren said at the time that the theft was 
thought to have been commissioned by a private art lover since the 
paintings are virtually unsellable on the open market 
beeren said the record loss figure was in part due to the 
astronomical prices fetched recently by van gogh paintings at 
auctions 
last november an unidentified collector paid 53 million for 
van goghs irises at a new york auction 
eight months earlier the impressionist masters sunflowers 
was auctioned in london for 298 million 
however experts of the christies auction firm in london said 
soon after the amsterdam burglary that the three paintings were 
worth only 11 million 
the theft also sparked a public debate on the security of the 
dutch artistic collections critics said too little was being done 
to protect the nations art treasures from often highly 
professional thieves 
the predawn burglary on may 20 triggered only an electronic 
alarm at the museum which has 3200 artworks mostly modern but 
no night guard 
it took 20 minutes for police to arrive on the scene of the 
burglary reportedly because the museums private security company 
failed to immediately alert authorities 
</TEXT>
