<TEXT>
a report from the international monetary fund 
acknowledges that poor people have been hurt by policies it has 
pressed on third world countries with the support of the united 
states 
in the past the imf has stressed that countries will be worse 
off if they delay the austerity policies such as devaluation of 
currencies and cuts in government spending usually required as a 
condition for imf loans 
the fund is owned by 151 governments with the united states 
holding the biggest block of votes at the end of march poor 
countries owed the fund 286 billion 
though founded in an effort to keep all currencies stable in 
recent years the fund has spent its money almost entirely on 
helping about 80 poor countries keep up with their debt much of it 
owed to the us government and banks 
although many of the major policy instruments improved the 
position of the dominant poverty groups in the sample countries 
other poverty groups were made worse off in the short run the 
new report says 
it chooses seven sample countries whose governments in recent 
years have adopted adjustment programs in order to get loans 
from the fund chile dominican republic ghana kenya 
philippines sri lanka and thailand 
the authors are five members of the fund staff led by an 
american peter s heller the fund distributed the report this 
week from its headquarters in washington 
the statement that introduces it comes from michel camdessus 
the funds french managing director 
adjustment does not have to lower basic human standards 
the more that adjustment efforts give proper weight to social 
realities especially the implications for the poorest the more 
successful they are likely to be 
large groups of poor people in the cities of chile the 
dominican republic and the philippines suffered from devaluations 
it says 
for the philippines the report tells how spending on health and 
schools was cut devaluation and restrictions on imports raised 
prices sharply while restrictions on the supply of money held down 
the number of jobs and the amount of wages 
in the dominican republic basic items were subsidized by a high 
exchange rate for the peso when the rate was lowered there was 
what the report calls major social unrest 
more than 50 people died in the dominican rioting of 1984 
sharp cuts in government spending may have hurt the poor in the 
long run as well as the short run in sri lanka and kenya according 
to the report but it adds that the cuts might have been even 
greater if there had been no agreement between the governments and 
the fund 
a rise in the tax on beer hit the people of ghana and kenya 
though not perhaps in welfare terms the report adds 
on the positive side the report says fund programs brought more 
credit for poor farmers in the dominican republic and sri lanka and 
the removal of price controls helped cut rents in the philippines 
and ghana 
it also says that lowering the exchange rate helped increased 
the real earnings of poor people in the country who were raising 
crops for export in ghana and to a lesser extent in kenya and the 
philippines 
