a leading reformer says he expects mikhail s 
gorbachevs liberalization drive to prevail at next months crucial 
party conference despite conservatives success at blocking some of 
its backers from attending 
the soviet leaders policies and programs are sufficiently 
strong to carry the conference prominent political scientist 
fyodor m burlatsky said monday he is among those who have been 
excluded 
the communist party conference the first since 1941 will lay 
out a a slate of policy decisions and proposals forming a blueprint 
for legislative changes it will amount to passing judgment on 
gorbachevs wideranging program of social and economic reforms 
known as perestroika 
the selection of the 5000 delegates to the june 28 conference 
has already turned into a showdown between backers of reform and 
those who seek to limit change often to preserve their privileges 
burlatsky said the conference will not name any new people to 
the 300member policymaking central committee in part to protect 
the committee headed by gorbachev from changes viewed as harmful 
if elections to the party conference have become so difficult 
how do we know elections to the central committee wont be tied up 
by some of these negative factors he asked 
burlatsky fell with the fortunes of nikita s khrushchev the 
late former premier but resurfaced to back gorbachevs 
perestroika campaign 
he said the partys charter does not spell out procedures for 
selecting delegates to party conferences we are learning 
democracy finding a style as we go it is certainly experimental 
since the last party conference was in 1941 times have changed 
radically and old ways of choosing delegates are no longer 
relevant the political scientist said 
instances where gorbachevs backers failed to get elected as 
delegates were sometimes the result of individual party officials 
striking the backers names from lists forwarded by factories 
