<TEXT>
the supreme court today unanimously struck 
down the way ohio promotes through tax credits the use of 
gasohol a motor vehicle fuel less environmentally troublesome 
than gasoline 
the court ruled that the ohio taxcredit scheme challenged by a 
gasohol producer in indiana interferes unconstitutionally with 
interstate commerce 
gasohol is the common name for a blend of 90 percent gasoline 
and 10 percent ethanol a 199proof alcohol derived from corn and 
other sources 
use of gasohol reduces the toxic emissions from leaded motor 
vehicle fuels to advance environmental goals most states and the 
federal government have offered tax credits for the production and 
sale of gasohol 
prior to 1985 ohio offered reductions in its fuel taxes for 
fuels containing ethanol regardless or where the ethanol was 
produced 
but since 1985 the state legislature has extended the credit to 
gasohol containing ethanol produced out of state only if it comes 
from a state in which ohioproduced ethanol receives a tax credit 
the credit for gasohol amounts to about 25 cents per gallon 
the reciprocity feature of the state law was challenged by new 
energy co of indiana which produces gasohol at its south bend 
ind plant and in 1985 was shipping about 25 percent of its output 
to ohio distributors 
new energy said it was priced out of the market in ohio when it 
lost its tax incentives 
the ohio supreme court struck down the taxcredit law as 
unconstitutional by a 43 vote in late 1986 but shortly thereafter 
two of the justices in the courts majority were voted out of 
office 
in 1986 the newly constituted state court granted a rehearing 
and ohios tax credit for ethanol was upheld 
today the nations highest court said the ohio supreme court 
was wrong 
scalia said the law imposes an economic disadvantage upon 
outofstate sellers and the promise to remove that if reciprocity 
is accepted no more justifies disparity of treatment than it would 
justify categorical exclusion 
the case is new energy co vs limbach 87654 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

