the supreme court today gave federal 
regulators broad power to oust bank executives from their jobs 
temporarily when the executives are accused of serious crimes 
in a 90 ruling the court said the federal deposit insurance 
corp acted properly in suspending an iowa bank president 
the justices upheld a law permitting the fdic to suspend a bank 
executive accused of serious wrongdoing for up to 90 days while the 
agency decides the executives appeal for reinstatement 
justice john paul stevens writing for the court said a bank 
executives interest in continued employment is without doubt an 
important interest that ought not be interrupted without 
substantial justification 
but stevens said a suspended officer also has an interest in 
seeing that a decision concerning his or her continued suspension 
is not made with excessive haste 
the case stems from the indictment in 1986 of james e mallen 
president of the now defunct farmers state bank of kanawha iowa 
on charges he made false statements to the fdic 
mallen was accused of concealing financial interests in other 
businesses and of concealing loans his banks made his small 
agricultural bank in a town of 750 people had assets of 18 million 
he was convicted in federal court last year and sentenced to 
three years in prison and fined 10000 he was ordered to spend 
only 60 days in jail and the rest of the sentence was suspended 
prior to his criminal trial the fdic barred him from continuing 
as bank president and director prohibited him from taking part in 
running the bank and said he could not vote his stock in the banks 
holding company 
the fdic acted under a law empowering federal banking regulators 
to suspend executives charged with crimes involving dishonesty or 
breach of trust that are punishable by imprisonment for more than 
one year 
the law gives the executive a right to appeal to the regulatory 
agency but the statute allows the agency to take up to three 
months to resolve the appeal 
moreover the law does not guarantee the banker a chance to 
present oral arguments in making the appeal 
a federal judge ruled mallens rights were violated by the 
suspension and by the ban on oral testimony to the fdic 
the reagan administration on behalf of the fdic appealed the 
ruling to the supreme court 
the case is fdic vs mallen 8782 
