<TEXT>
the supreme court in a decision the reagan 
administration says could save consumers an estimated 100 million 
a year cleared the way today for price deregulation of some 
natural gas 
the justices 80 reversed an appeals court ruling that had 
placed a floor under the gas prices 
the appeals court ruling was challenged by the administration 
the new york state public service commission and natural gas 
distributors who buy from producers 
the dispute was over interpretation of the natural gas policy 
act of 1978 a federal law that phases out regulation of natural 
gas prices and is designed to assure an adequate supply of gas for 
delivery across state lines 
prior to the laws enactment there was a ceiling on the price 
of gas sold interstate but no such regulation for gas produced and 
sold within the same state 
the twotier system prompted producers to commit more of their 
supplies to the intrastate market causing shortages in interstate 
supplies of natural gas 
the 1978 law created a complicated system of phasing out price 
controls that divides gas into three categories old new and 
difficulttoproduce gas 
generally the price regulations applied more to old gas and 
lifted controls for new gas to encourage discoveries and production 
old gas is that produced from wells operating before the law was 
passed and new gas is that from wells that began producing after 
the laws passage the third category covers gas produced by 
particuarly highcost methods such as that obtained from between 
layers of more impervious rock 
the gas supplies involved in the case decided today overlap the 
categories qualifying for both regulated and deregulated treatment 
under the 1978 law 
the federal energy regulatory commission in 1985 eliminated 
controls for such dually qualified gas allowing the price to 
be determined by the free market 
the commission said maintaining controls would lead to a 
regulated price higher than the freemarket price an opposite 
effect from the one intended by congress in enacting the 1978 law 
but the 10th circuit court acting on appeals by gas producers 
said the commissions deregulation rule violated the 1978 law 
writing for the high court today justice william j brennan 
said the appeals court wrongly overturned the commissions rule he 
said the commissions interpretation of the 1978 law was correct 
justice byron r white did not participate in the case for 
unannounced reasons 
the case is ferc vs martin exploration management co 87363 
</TEXT>
