<TEXT>
a sharpened consumer appetite for fish and 
seafood offers an opportunity for american farmers to reel in a 
share of a growing worldwide aquaculture industry says a report by 
the agriculture department 
expanding world population and growing consumer demands have 
already forced some nations to harvest previously underutilized 
species of fish and seafood and to develop alternative sources 
the report said 
many commercial fisheries which harvest from the wild are 
approaching their maximum sustainable yield it added thus 
aquaculture growing fish or other aquatic life in a controlled 
environment is expanding 
americans are also honing their appetites last year consuming 
more fish and seafood per person than veal lamb and mutton 
roasting chicken or turkey beef pork and broiler chicken 
however remain far in the lead as american favorites 
in 1980 aquaculture accounted for 13 percent of the global 
production of aquatic foods and goods up from 7 percent in 1970 
industry sources indicate that by the year 2010 aquaculture will 
provide 25 percent of the worldwide aquatic harvest 
the report was included in the june issue of agricultural 
outlook magazine issued by the departments economic research 
service the article was written by economists mike dicks and dave 
harvey 
by 1981 total us fish consumption had grown 30 percent from 
1970 about 47 percent was imported 
population growth accounts for only half the increase the 
report added per capita us consumption of fish and shellfish 
has grown reaching a record 154 pounds edible weight in 1987 
it is expected to expand another 50 percent by 2010 
dicks said in a telephone interview that the 1987 per capita 
consumption figure included only 05 pound of the estimated 3 to 5 
pounds per capita of us aquaculture production the half pound 
he said only included catfish and none of the other species 
ranging from trout and salmon to oysters and shrimp 
despite the recent increases us per capita fish and seafood 
consumption is well behind europe which averages 40 to 45 pounds 
per person and japan which averages 130 to 140 pounds annually 
per capita consumption of veal last year by americans averaged 
15 pounds lamb and mutton 13 mature chicken 25 and turkey 
152 beef consumption was 755 pounds pork 588 and broiler 
chicken 601 those are retail weights as sold by grocery stores 
the us aquaculture industry fish farming has expanded 
greatly in recent years but still is led by catfish produced 
primarily in the south in 1986 for example the us aquaculture 
harvest was nearly 620 million pounds valued at more than 496 
million 
of those amounts catfish comprised 327 million pounds worth 
229 million to growers the report showed 
comparatively in 1980 the total harvest was 203 million pounds 
valued at 192 million with catfish comprising less than 77 
million pounds at a value of 54 million 
catfish crawfish salmon and trout make up about 90 percent of 
