<TEXT>
here at a glance are highlights of actions 
taken monday by the supreme court 
 
gray market 
 
the court ruled the bulk of socalled gray market goods are 
legal giving a green light to a big part of a multibilliondollar 
business that allows consumers to buy costly brandname imports at 
steep discounts 
in another case the court ruled that states sometimes may 
execute convicted murderers even if their constitutional right to a 
lawyers help was violated 
the case is k mart vs cartier 86495 
 
capital punishment 
 
the court ruled that states sometimes may execute convicted 
murderers even if their constitutional right to a lawyers help was 
violated 
by a 53 vote the justices said for the first time that errors 
in which a convicted murderers constitutional right to a lawyers 
help was violated may be deemed harmless 
but the justices voted 80 in stating that such an error in the 
prosecution of convicted texas murderer john satterwhite was not 
harmless the decision overturned his death sentence 
the case is satterwhite vs texas 866284 
 
firefighters 
 
the court refused to reinstate an affirmative action plan 
designed to increase the number of blacks in the district of 
columbia fire department 
the justices without comment let stand a ruling that the plan 
calling for hiring at least six blacks for every l0 job openings 
unlawfully discriminates against whites 
the case is barry vs us 871150 
 
cable access 
 
the court refused to resurrect federal rules that would force 
cable television operators to carry all local tv signals on their 
systems 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that struck down 
as unconstitutional interim mustcarry rules adopted by the 
federal communications commissions in 1986 
the cases are office of communications of the united church of 
christ vs fcc 871487 corporation for public broadcasting vs 
century communications 871506 national association of 
broadcasters vs century communications 871510 and association 
of independent television stations vs century communications 
871551 
 
checkkiting 
 
the court left intact a 25 million fine against a businessman 
for what prosecutors called the biggest checkkiting fraud in the 
history of american banking 
the court citing the lack of a substantial federal 
question rejected a challenge to a new york law that says those 
convicted in such schemes may be forced to pay fines equal to twice 
the amount gained through their criminal conduct 
the case is halloran vs new york 871595 
 
tampons 
 
the court refused to reduce a jury award of more than 112 
million won from a tampon manufacturer by the family of a kansas 
woman who died of toxic shock syndrome 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by playtex 
holdings inc seeking to reduce the award 
the case is playtex holdings vs ogilvie 871021 
 
natural gas 
 
the supreme court in a decision the reagan administration says 
could save consumers an estimated 100 million a year cleared the 
way today for price deregulation of some natural gas 
the justices in an 80 decision reversed an appeals court 
ruling that had placed a floor under the gas prices 
the case is ferc vs martin exploration management co 87363 
 
punitive damages 
 
the court let stand a 5 million punitivedamages award won by a 
california savings and loan association against an ohiobased 
insurance company 
the justices over two dissenting votes refused to hear 
arguments that the award believed to be the largest of its kind 
ever upheld in california courts is unconstitutionally excessive 
the case is ohio casualty insurance co vs downey savings and 
loan association 87159 
