an increase in the state sales tax from 
5 percent to 6 percent is expected to pump 704 million into the 
states hardpressed treasury between now and july 1 1989 
paul mckown president of the west virginia retailers 
association said that despite objections to the higher tax which 
was to take effect at midnight tuesday most people feel they 
have an obligation to participate and pay the bills of the state 
and this is one way of doing it 
the tax increase was part of an elaborate compromise worked out 
among the governor and the legislature as they battled over 
finances earlier this year when the state was forced to borrow 80 
million on a shortterm basis to meet operating expenses 
the compromise was approved during the march 22 oneday special 
session of the legislature the increased sales tax is expected to 
raise 54 million for the remaining month of this fiscal year and 
and an estimated 65 million during the fiscal year that starts 
july 1 
it is due to expire on june 30 1989 although some merchants 
have said they expect it to become permanent after the general 
election in november 
the tax was included in a bill that allowed the governor to 
borrow 30 million from the state black lung fund for miners to 
meet a backlog in medicaid payments for medical treatment for the 
poor the sales tax is to be used in part for the payback on the 
loan money 
mckown said the temporary tax will cause little inconvenience 
for the states 25000 to 30000 retailers who collect and send 
the tax to the state tax department 
the states border counties may see a temporary exodus of 
customers to other states but mckown said he does not expect that 
to last long if it even occurs surrounding kentucky 
pennsylvania ohio and maryland have a 5 percent sales tax 
virginia has a 4 percent tax rate 
