<TEXT>
prices farmers got for raw products in may 
averaged 31 percent over april levels and were 47 percent over 
their mark for the same month last year the agriculture department 
said tuesday 
higher prices for hogs oranges soybeans and broilers were 
partially offset by lower prices for tomatoes onions milk and 
upland cotton the departments agricultural statistics board 
said in its preliminary report 
may farm commodity prices averaged 134 percent of a 1977 base 
used for comparison according to the preliminary figures a year 
ago the index was 128 
hog prices climbed to their highest levels since october on 
average while cattle rose to the top levels since may 1979 
soybeans marked the largest monthto month increase in more than 
four years 58 cents a bushel and broilers were 55 cents a pound 
over their april mark 
according to usda economists net cash income of farmers set a 
record of about 57 billion in 1987 this years net the 
difference between cash receipts and cash expenses may be in the 
50 billion55 billion range 
consumer food prices are expected to rise 2 percent to 4 percent 
this year compared with a 42 percent average increase in 1987 
preliminary may figures based mainly on midmonth averages 
showed livestock and poultry prices up 27 percent from both april 
and may 1987 
higher prices for hogs broilers and beef cattle more than 
offset lower prices for milk eggs and calves usda said 
crop prices overall were up 45 percent from april and 74 
percent above the levels of a year ago 
the price index for oilbearing crops which consist mainly of 
soybeans was up 74 percent from the previous month and 26 percent 
above the may 1987 level 
prices paid to commercial vegetable growers decreased 12 percent 
from aprils levels and 11 percent from last year usda attributed 
most of the change to lower prices for tomatoes onions and sweet 
corn 
