<DOCNO> AP880531-0182 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
lick observatory a pioneering 
mountaintop astronomical complex that once boasted the worlds 
largest telescope observes its 100th skywatching anniversary 
wednesday 
it was at lick where edward barnard found the fifth moon of 
jupiter where the existence was established of innumerable distant 
galaxies where expansion of the universe was mapped and where 
scientists studied how stars form and age 
businessman james lick who set up a trust and earmarked 
700000 for construction of the telescope and observatory made 
his orders clear build a powerful telescope superior and more 
powerful than any telescope yet made 
lick died in 1876 12 years before the observatory was ready for 
operation but his remains were moved to mount hamiliton in january 
1887 and placed in a vault at the base of the lick telescope 
astronomy was a strange choice for lick who got his start 
making pianos in south america made a fortune in california real 
estate and once owned catalina island and big pieces of downtown 
san francisco 
lick observatory was built on 4430foot mount hamilton and an 
immense 36inch lens was mounted on a 57foot tube then the 
worlds biggest telescope 
it was the first real demonstration of the value of being on a 
mountaintop said joseph miller an assistant lick director 
noting that before lick most observatories were in cities 
later mountaintop observatories became standard encouraging 
the development of other pristine sites including those in chile 
hawaii and southern california 
owned and operated by the university of califoria the 
observatory 60 miles south of san francisco has lost some of its 
glitter but its seven telescope domes offices and workshops have 
a world reputation for solid valuable work 
the telescope still functions second in size only to the 
40inch refracting telescope at yerkes observatory in wisconsin 
the lick telescopes today also include the 120inch shane 
reflector a 40inch reflector two 24inch reflectors and a twin 
20inch refractor the telescopes are used all the time and are 
most in demand for moonless nights 
lick also pioneered the use of reflecting telescopes which use 
a mirror instead of a lens to focus light 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

