the hospital announced the development in a statement by 
neurologist edward hitchcock whose team carried out britains 
first known fetal braincell transplants in march and april 
parkinsons disease is a potentially fatal condition that causes 
gradual loss of muscle control fetal tissue is thought to 
stimulate production of dopamine a brain chemical lacking in 
parkinsons disease 
hitchcocks disclosure last month that he used the experimental 
procedure provoked controversy critics complained it reduced the 
aborted fetus to the status of a human spare part others welcomed 
it as a possible medical breakthrough 
the us department of health and human services has banned 
government scientists from carrying out surgery using tissue from 
aborted fetuses pending study of the ethical legal and medical 
questions involved 
the first documented use of the experimental procedure was 
reported in january when surgeons in mexico city said they 
injected tissue from a miscarried fetus into the brains of two 
parkinsons sufferers last september swedish doctors subsequently 
reported use of the technique with disappointing results 
hitchcock said last month that his team transplanted fetal brain 
cells into a 60yearold woman and a 41yearold man both of whom 
were said to have shown dramatic improvement 
hitchcock said the latest operation was carried out under 
guidelines issued by the british medical association last month 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

