<TEXT>
the us supreme court granted a stay of 
execution for condemned georgia death row inmate son h fleming on 
tuesday a day before he was scheduled to die in the states 
electric chair 
the high court granted the stay with no immediate comment 
except to note that chief justice william h rehnquist and justices 
byron white and sandra day oconnor dissented said court 
spokeswoman kathy arberg 
fleming 58 was scheduled to die at 7 pm wednesday for the 
1976 slaying of ray city police chief ed giddens if the stay had 
not been granted he would have been the 99th person put to death 
since the supreme court allowed states to restore the death penalty 
in 1976 georgia has killed 12 people 
giddens was abducted and killed after he stopped a car matching 
the description of one used in a robbery he had pleaded for his 
life and told his captors he planned to retire the next day 
according to trial testimony 
henry willis also received a death sentence for the slaying but 
no execution date has been set a third defendant larry fleming 
nephew of son fleming was sentenced to life in prison 
earlier tuesday flemings family had asked the state board of 
pardons and paroles to block the execution 
son flemings attorney ken shapiro said tuesdays appeal was 
virtually the same as one filed two years ago when fleming came 
within hours of execution the latest petition has a supplement 
containing a statement from flemings son shapiro said 
the earlier appeal raised questions about flemings role in the 
crime and cited three heart attacks fleming has suffered during 12 
years on death row the 11th us circuit court of appeals stayed 
the execution 
parole board chairman wayne snow said after the 40minute closed 
hearing that the board would review the new appeal through the 
afternoon he said the board would consider flemings frail health 
and his relatives arguments 
about 10 members of flemingss family attended the hearing 
including four of his sisters and his younger brother handy 
