<TEXT>
researchers studying four aidsinfected men who 
appeared to stop producing detectable antibodies to the disease 
confirmed the finding tuesday and said the virus may have stopped 
reproducing in those patients 
tests to pinpoint aids and protect blood supplies are based upon 
detection of the antibodies produced naturally by the body to fight 
the virus but homayoon farzadegan and alfred j saah both 
professors of epidemiology at the johns hopkins school of public 
health said their findings do not imply increased dangers of blood 
supply contamination 
i dont think the risk to the blood supply is any different 
today than it was yesterday said saah during a news conference 
the instances of aids victims who stop producing detectable 
antibodies to the disease are very very rare and so far have 
only been observed in those who show small amounts of the virus 
present in their bodies saah said 
four of 1000 homosexual men who participated in the 
researchers continuing study showed the loss of antibodies up to 
3 years ago and continue to test negative 
usually when an infected person loses hiv1 antibodies he or 
she is in the end stages of aids and has a deteriorated immune 
system said b frank polk also a professor of epidemiology at 
the school and coauthor of a report on the study 
but the four men had no clinical symptoms of illness such as 
swollen lymph glands or abnormal counts of the white blood cells 
targeted by the virus he added 
the researchers reported their findings in june 1987 but could 
not determine whether the men were properly diagnosed as having 
aids initially and whether mistakes had been made in laboratory 
tests 
during followup the researchers used a new method to test for 
the virus rather than the antibody and have determined that the men 
show evidence of infection but not antibodies to the aids virus 
the new test called polymerase chain reaction assay or pcr 
magnifies the presence of the virus genetic material up to 1 
million times 
farzadegan speculated that the virus may go into a latent phase 
during which it does not reproduce 
we dont know if something in the virus itself is defective 
and causing it not to reproduce or whether it is something within 
the host saah said adding that researchers have not determined 
whether the disease is transmissible during this phase 
aids is caused by a virus that attacks the bodys immune system 
leaving victims susceptible to fatal infections and cancers it is 
most often transmitted by sexual contact or by drug abusers sharing 
contaminated hypodermic needles and syringes 
all of the men who participated in the initial report are 
participants in the multicenter aids cohort study macs that 
follows nearly 5000 homosexual and bisexual men in baltimore los 
angeles chicago and pittsburgh to document the natural progression 
of aids 
the latest findings are to be published in the june 1 issue of 
annals of internal medicine 
