he and other mexican authorities believe the unwritten law of 
supply and demand is winning out over the 1986 us immigration 
reform and control act also known as the simpsonrodino law even 
though jobs are going begging in northern mexico 
the undocumented migrants continue entering the united states 
as if there never had been a simpsonrodino law jorge 
bustamante director of the tijuanabased northern border college 
and a leading critic of the immigration law wrote in a recent 
newspaper column 
the laws supporters say its intent is to help the united 
states regain control of its borders 
us ambassador charles pilliod jr said in midmay however 
that the law was not conceived to eliminate the movement of 
mexican workers to the united states 
the united states needs these workers not only in the farm 
area but also in the many service sectors such as food outlets 
hotels etc pilliod said in a speech to the american chamber of 
commerce in mexico city 
the law gave legal status to aliens who were able to prove they 
have lived in the united states at least since 1982 in doing so 
the alients ensured themselves of such rights as a minimum wage 
health care and education 
those who entered the united states after 1982 without legal 
documentation remain subject to deportation 
pilliod said however that predictions of mass deportations are 
unfair 
granted the border patrol will continue to apprehend and 
return undocumented aliens to their home countries as always but 
there are no plans for mass roundups he said 
bustamante and others contend that the united states cannot 
reverse a 40year trend with a law because working in the united 
states without documents if necessary has become part of the 
lifestyle of thousands of mexican families 
mexicans who go to work in the united states even those taking 
the most menial jobs can earn five to 10 times what they earn at 
home where the minimum wage is the equivalent of about 345 a day 
the northern border college estimates mexicans working in the 
united states generate about 1 billion in foreign income for 
mexico 
the simpsonrodino law gave illegal aliens who met certain 
requirements until may 4 to apply for legal status in the united 
states the majority of the more than 16 million people who 
applied are mexican 
but us immigration officials estimate that half or more of the 
6 million to 7 million illegal aliens in the united states are 
mexican 
and nobody is reporting either a mass exodus or mass 
deportations of mexicans since the may 4 deadline passed 
just as we predicted based on investigations we do at the 
northern border college nothing extraordinary has happened since 
may 5 bustamante wrote in excelsior of mexico city 
northern border college offices from tijuana to matamoros have 
been studying undocumented workers for three years 
for them the main factor that determines their willingness to 
run the risks is the labor market bustamante wrote as long as 
they keep hiring they will continue entering 
a key intent of the simpsonrodino law is to stop the hiring of 
illegal aliens by us employers 
in the toughest provision of the law employers who knowingly 
hire undocumented workers can receive stiff fines and other 
sanctions agricultural employers have until dec 1 before 
sanctioning begins 
meanwhile the crossings continue 
the majority of those who cross here are farm workers and 
theyve been given special considerations said mayor ernesto 
