editors note hes a seasoned practitioner of a relatively 
new steadily booming and widely mistrusted profession in america 
david sawyer political consultant didnt have an entry in the 
recent presidential primaries but he has some definite views on 
why the winners won and the losers lost 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
david sawyer sat on the sidelines during the 
presidential primaries just ended an unusual place for him in a 
hot election campaign but there he sat like a maestro in the 
audience enjoying it making notes 
dole he says reflecting on the campaign that one writer 
likened to a demolition derby made some errors that hurt him 
ruined him so he lost bush won bush made few errors dukakis on 
the other side made few errors and dukakis won 
david sawyer is a political consultant 
he is a democrat and works only for democrats he also is a 
seasoned practitioner of a relatively new steadily booming and 
widely mistrusted profession in america 
one popular perception of a political consultant is that of a 
modernday machiavelli who knows how to use electronic guile to 
manipulate a benighted electorate into mistaking form for substance 
nonsense says sawyer but it is obvious that he feels some 
of the skills that good political consultants do bring to a 
campaign were lacking in some of the races this spring 
robert doles for instance the republican senator in sawyers 
view failed badly in organizing his campaign and developing his 
strategy he didnt appoint a strong team he tried to run it all 
himself and you cant do that dole he feels would have made a 
more formidable opponent for dukakis 
george bush on the other hand put together a superb 
organization the campaign carried the candidate people who run a 
good campaign have the edge 
michael dukakis dukakis enters the fall campaign much less 
damaged than walter mondale was when he entered the 84 campaign 
dukakis is beholden to none of the special interest groups that 
mondale was identified with dukakis ran a simply fine campaign and 
it paid off 
that in short sawyer explains is the job of the consultant 
to give his candidate the edge 
david sawyer is 52 trim with thinning gray hair and gray eyes 
whatever it is that he and his partner scott miller do to gain 
that edge they are apparently financially successful at it their 
wellappointed suite of offices overlook central park in one of 
manhattans classiest midtown neighborhoods 
in the past five years the sawyermiller group has doubled in 
size from 20 to 40 reflecting the meteoric rise in america of the 
political consulting trade 
they even have a trade association and it has grown from 75 
members 10 years ago to 650 today its president brad oleary 
estimates that as many as 3000 professionals in america may be 
considered political consultants 
sawyer also represents a certain coming of age in the state of 
the art 
the consulting fraternity had its origins in the advertising 
agencies summoned off madison avenue by politicians a practice 
roundly criticized in the 1968 book the selling of the 
president 
in an ironic turnaround sawyer has expanded into the commercial 
field using techniques learned in political campaigns he 
represents political candidates but also cocacola apple computer 
and a dozen or so others mainly those dealing with unexpected 
market changes and stiff competition 
political campaigns require his companys complete attention 
sawyer says and mainly for that reason he sat out the primaries 
we felt we wouldnt be able to give our commercial work all it 
deserves if we do any political work this year it will be in the 
general election campaign 
this election year an estimated 18 billion will be spent on 
politics with 500 million going for tv ads and 100 million for 
political consultants for that kind of money politicians must 
consider a consultants service as something more than that of a 
debating coach 
true says sawyer but hardly more sinister 
a political campaign is like a war says sawyer in a 
limited period of time you have to seize certain territory and hold 
it it involves strategy and tactics i work on both levels 
the strategic team about 10 people are experts in various 
categories who determine how the candidate positions himself how 
he contrasts himself with his opponents which issues in the array 
of issues he believes in should be the key issues of the campaign 
it was on the strategic level that albert gore stumbled 
according to sawyer 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0256 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
although he was very attractive he began to be seen as 
opportunistic changing his strategy he ran as a defense 
candidate then as a southern candidate then as a jewish 
candidate then as an economic populist candidate 
it is very important to develop a singleminded clear 
strategy gore ended up with four or five different strategies 
which made it difficult for any one of them to be heard 
dukakis for his part sawyer says had such great strength in 
terms of money credibility as a sitting governor and such a 
firstrate campaign organization it was tough to compete against 
him of all the contending democrats dukakis emerged in sawyers 
view as the most electable in november 
the tactical teams job says sawyer is to figure out how to 
communicate a candidates complex agenda often in 30second bites 
not just for tv spots the nightly news is done in 30second 
bites as well or less its the nature of the business nowadays 
and it isnt all bad you can express your position on some pretty 
complex issues in 30 seconds 
for example i oppose any further aid to the contras three 
seconds if elected i would ask congress to raise taxes 10 
percent across the board to pay off our deficit five seconds 
the reasoning the subtleties come out in the formal debates 
and the print media the electorate in my opinion has never been 
better informed about the position of the candidates on any issue 
and on his or her character 
the tacticians techniques helped along by advanced technology 
including instant polling videotape and federal express are where 
consultants show their battlefield savvy 
you have to be able to take advantage of every opportunity 
change your strategy on a moments notice often its a matter of 
timing 
sawyer demonstrated this last year in the kentucky democratic 
primary sawyers firm like nearly all consultant firms 
represents candidates of only one party that race put him up 
against two others with similar reputations as heavy hitters among 
democrats bob squier representing former gov john y brown the 
early favorite and david doak and robert shrum representing 
thenlt gov steve beshear the leading challenger 
sawyers candidate was wallace wilkinson a political unknown 
who registered only about 5 percent in the polls and was given 
little chance to improve 
little chance that is until the last two weeks of the campaign 
our two opponents began attacking each other with spots 
accusing each other of all sorts of things and both advocated a 
tax increase 
we discovered through polls that the voters disapproved of 
the negative campaigns they were waging against each other so we 
moved in quickly we said in effect that they were both right in 
their accusations and we pushed for a lottery that we had 
advocated all along instead of new taxes 
we had the overall strategy but we needed an opening to 
execute it and that gave us the opening we exploited it call it 
guerrilla tactics 
whatever you call it wallace wilkinson is now governor of 
kentucky 
could any campaign consultants tactics have saved gary hart 
absolutely not hart was doomed as soon as the donna rice 
episode came out the most important thing people need to have is 
trust in their leader trust in his judgement and his character 
hart sacrificed any trust the people could have had in him 
sawyer was lured into politics from a career as a producer of 
documentary films in 1970 when he was asked to do some film work 
for a candidate for governor of illinois by 1974 he was into 
political consulting with both feet 
his batting average has stayed at about 750 good enough for 
the big leagues clients include four sitting senators and six 
governors and for an expanding foreign trade as well his clients 
also include corazon aquino president of the philippines and 
israels foreign minister shimon peres 
he has taken advantage of every technological advance as have 
his colleagues but in his view the most important electioneering 
change in the past decade has been not in sophisticated technology 
but the evergrowing sophistication of voters 
americans are exposed to commercial advertising more 
aggressive than ever before to expanded news coverage because of 
satellite transmissions and you just dont manipulate them you 
cant 
tv is like an xray machine voters can see through false 
statements or sloganeering instead of substantive debate 
</TEXT>
