a fly fisherman doesnt have to wear 
designer labels or own expensive gear to land the big ones a trout 
with a brain the size of a pea doesnt discriminate between l l 
bean and levis 
but serious anglers nearly all agree that collecting gadgets 
perusing catalogs and spending a snowy winters day inside a 
fishing equipment store is part of the ritual 
like one great beauty surreptitiously ogling anothers jewels 
fly fishermen check out each others tackle with discriminating 
eyes 
theres a genteel snobbery in showing up on opening day along 
the beaver kill river in new york sporting an antique hiram leonard 
split tonkin bamboo rod a wheatley fly box a few irresistibles 
tied by harry or elsie darbee and a faded but muchbeloved red 
shirt thats survived being stuffed into duffles from ireland to 
new zealand and back again by way of patagonia and venezuela 
in spite of sneaking suspicions that fish get spooked by red 
