editors note in an affluent town on the connecticut river a 
new subdivision features antique homes that have been dismantled 
rebuilt and equipped with todays conveniences such as burglar 
alarms and air conditioning the price tag 800000 to 12 
million 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
an 18th century tavern with trees sprouting 
through the floorboards seemed destined to be razed in a 
firefighting drill until it was rescued by a couple of connecticut 
developers who look to the past to find fancy homes for the future 
now it will be restored with modern conveniences added and 
become one of the dozen or so antique homes in an unusual 33acre 
subdivision in this affluent town on the connecticut river 
developers harry p broom jr and william oberg are scouring the 
countryside for other vintage homes for the subdivision they call 
sterling meadows the homes when finished will carry a modern 
price tag of 800000 to 12 million broom and oberg say they 
havent tried to sell any yet 
the former owner of the old tavern they said sold it to them 
rather than to the salem fire department which was going to burn 
it down for a firefighting drill 
the problem is most old houses are accidents of geography 
says oberg 32 of essex who left a career in finance more than 
two years ago to become a developer 
what used to be a convenient location on the main road is now 
a busy commercial district with a lot of traffic going by and they 
end up being torn down for a new office building a new apartment 
building or one thing or another 
oberg says the partnership has purchased five buildings for its 
subdivision and is still looking for others to fill the seven other 
lots four buildings are now being reconstructed at the site a 
concrete foundation is ready for a federalstyle home from 
massachusetts that dates to around 1800 
they expect to complete the development in about three years 
the first step is saving the buildings a painstaking task the 
partnership has paid 5000 to 20000 for the relics and spends 
five to six weeks dismantling them 
with a crew of carpenters supplied by brooms other business 
hb broom housewright inc a restoration company nearly 
everything is saved from frame and windows to mantels and 
floorboards 
broom and oberg remain true to each buildings original design 
which means for example rebuilding six fireplaces in the former 
salem tavern but the structures are outfitted with modern 
conveniences such as burglar alarm systems and central air 
conditioning 
when we rebuild these houses were using all the original 
features and restoring the house as best we can but were not 
building museums says broom 44 of lyme whose office is in a 
building built in 1770 to serve as a general store for steamships 
on the connecticut river and the ferry that to this day shuttles 
between chester and hadlyme 
were building houses that are practical to live in 
the interiors are slightly modified with ells to accommodate the 
modern trappings of kitchens and bathrooms otherwise the homes are 
original right down to the slightly offcenter front doors on some 
they plan to pave the winding road leading to the development 
and line it with sugar maples stone walls and picket fences 
antique lampposts will be recreated based on a design borrowed 
from deerfield mass 
were trying to create the perfect new england environment 
oberg says we try not to change the details at all and take 
small liberties with the ells 
oberg is quick to dispel notions that the developers are trying 
to imitate sturbridge village in massachusetts or williamsburg in 
connecticut he says they confine their efforts to homes built 
between 1700 and 1815 and lean toward those in formal styles such 
as federal or georgian 
similar but smaller subdivisions of five relocated historic 
homes each are located in rural killingworth conn and in 
waitsfield vt 
oberg criticizes the socalled purist approach to 
restoration which is light on modern conveniences and heavy on 
dark interior colors 
the result when a socalled purist restores a house is that 
the houses tend to be dark and use dark colors and that is not 
quite what everybody would like he says 
the sterling meadows development has met the approval of town 
officials who are committed to 2 and 3acre zoning in order to 
preserve the towns atmosphere 
about 1910 people live in lymes 33 square miles homeowners 
include former new york city mayor john lindsay and brooklyn ny 
district attorney elizabeth holtzman 
if youre gonna have development of that nature you could do 
no better than skip broom says lyme first selectman john f 
yeomans referring to broom by his nickname theyre as good as 
any and better than most 
oberg and broom formed their partnership 2 years ago after 
oberg bought a tract of land alongside a 12acre parcel broom 
already owned oberg says he has had a lifelong interest in antique 
homes while broom quit a job as an analyst with shell oil co about 
15 years ago to start his restoration business 
i had a piece of land i bought as a investment and i always 
wanted to put antique houses on it says broom whose company has 
restored about 80 homes oddly enough he wanted to do the same 
thing 
</TEXT>
