<TEXT>
 
jacknifed columbia jean beauvoir 
 
in his 26 years jean beauvoir has packed wildly diverse 
experiences onto his musical resume including stints with the 
doowop flamingoes shock punkers plasmatics and little stevens 
political disciples of soul 
even beauvoirs appearance paints him as a musical maverick with 
the wild white mohawk hes sported for many years 
this personal history hardly prepares a listener for the musical 
conservatism of jacknifed beauvoirs second solo album 
jacknifed is a soulful contemporary dance album probably 
the first to be influenced by the success of terence trent darby 
the keyboards and guitars simmer but dont sizzle leaving room for 
beauvoirs songs to stretch and breathe 
both lyrically and musically beauvoir has the smarts to avoid 
tired cliches he also avoids anything distinctive that will get 
his songs noticed jacknifed is the type of record that would 
float by on the radio without causing any real reaction 
many of the songs such as standing on my own two feet and 
find my way home tread familiar themes of a solitary man trying 
to find his way in a hostile world 
beauvoir who wrote and produced the album along with playing 
most of the instruments has obvious talent hes still looking for 
the best way to show the world 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
the story of the clash vol 1 epic the clash 
 
they once advertised themselves as the only band that 
matters one member of the group was fired for political reasons 
the bands first hit single wasnt even listed on the cover of the 
london calling album 
who are the clash 
this onceimportant band dropped so quickly from the public 
consciousness it almost seems like theyve become a trivia 
question the time is ripe for a retrospective and epic records 
has obliged with the tworecord the story of the clash vol 1 
liking or hating the clash during their brief prime in the late 
1970s and early 80s was almost a political statement in itself 
punk rock set up two hostile camps one that loved the brash young 
toughs challenging the musical establishment the other threatened 
by them the bands aggressive workingclass politics also left 
little room for neutrality 
this often obscured the simple fact the clash was a terrific 
rock band one that quickly grew past the limitations of primitive 
punk but never lost the creative spark that went with it 
the retrospective while put together rather haphazardly makes 
that point abundantly clear 
the set cuts a wide swath through the glorious trash rock of 
should i stay or should i go the motown tribute train in 
vain the mainstream rock crunch of london calling the 
inspirational near ballad stay free and the adrenalin kick of 
janie jones 
oddly the record only includes two cuts from the sprawling 
threerecord sandinista cuts such as the title track or 
charlie dont surf would have been better than the subpar 
straight to hell included here from combat rock 
the record doesnt run chronologically side 3 is a tribute to 
the clashs infancy and side one sounds like a prototype for mick 
jones subsequent big audio dynamite group but the sequencing 
often seems random if not it would have been preferable to hear 
the band explain it through retrospective liner notes instead of 
the rambling reminiscence of a roadie included here 
still this is an illuminating trip through a time capsule and 
would make an especially worthy purchase for those who missed the 
clash the first time around 
</TEXT>
