<TEXT>
seemingly healthy cocaine users who drop 
dead may be victims of the drugs interference with the hearts 
electrical activity 
researchers edward avakian and mark bracken at the university of 
the pacific injected rats and rabbits dosages equivalent to a 
160pound chronic abuser who smokes or injects 15 grams or 
snorts 3 grams of cocaine a day 
their studies suggest that cocaine causes sudden cardiac death 
by triggering abnormal heart rhythms said avakian a 
physiologistpharmacologist many cocaineinduced arrhythmias are 
temporary but others called ventricular arrhythmias kill because 
they halt the hearts ability to pump 
the findings also suggest that while longterm daily cocaine 
users develop tolerance to the drugs effects on the heart they 
are particularly susceptible to sudden death if they stop taking it 
and then resume 
cocaine is not always available so one might not take it for 
one or two days avakian said a brief withdrawal of one or two 
days can put a user at much more risk especially during a stress 
situation like exercise 
the risk of death from injecting cocaine or smoking its 
freebase or crack forms is particularly high because much 
more is absorbed into blood where it can directly affect the 
heart he said 
avakian bracken a physiologist and colleagues set out to 
explain such deaths as those in 1986 of university of maryland 
basketball star len bias and cleveland browns football player don 
rogers as of early 1987 there had been eight such deaths among 49 
documented cases of cocaineinduced heart trouble according to 
research by dr jeffrey isner of new england medical center 
avakian and bracken who outlined their work at a federation of 
american societies for experimental biology meeting last month 
used 40 rabbits and 300 rats some received no cocaine others got 
daily doses for eight weeks 
some of the animals were killed 30 minutes after the last 
injection others were killed two days later to simulate withdrawal 
from cocaine 
the hearts were removed and kept pumping in laboratory 
containers filled with a blood substitute while researchers 
monitored heart electrical activity blood flow through coronary 
arteries and heart rate rhythm and contractions 
then the researchers added cocaine alone or cocaine and 
adrenalin to the blood substitute bathing the hearts adrenalin 
normally is produced by the body during exercise or other physical 
or emotional stress 
hearts from animals that got cocaine before they were killed 
showed more disruption of electrical impulse transmission probably 
because cocaine acts as a local anesthetic avakian said 
the studies also showed chronic cocaine use when combined with 
adrenalin constricts coronary arteries reducing blood flow to the 
heart the combination of cocaineinduced arrythmias and the 
decreased blood flow increases the odds of sudden death he said 
hearts from animals withdrawn from cocaine for two days were 
supersensitive to adrenalin and cocaine suggesting sudden death is 
more likely in chronic abusers who stop and start again 
particularly if they exercise or are otherwise stressed 
</TEXT>
