at hyatt hotel corp in chicago executives are 
basking in government praise of their model compliance with the new 
immigration law which makes it illegal to knowingly hire 
undocumented aliens 
but on the texas border a mexican fastfood chain fears 
possible raids by the immigration and naturalization service 
and in southern california a waterbedframe factory is 
challenging what it calls abusive and arbitrary ins inspection 
tactics in the first significant court test of the new laws 
sweeping employersanction provisions 
as the wednesday deadline looms for enforcement of those 
sanctions employers and immigration lawyers are giving the law and 
the ins a mixed review 
many say the agency has shown extraordinary tolerance and the 
new documentation requirements for employees are only a minor 
nuisance others contend immigration officers have failed to 
educate a large number of businesses and the paperwork is 
horrendously confusing 
my sense is that many employers arent complying with the 
law said ilene f lainer immigration specialist at the law firm 
of grotta glassman amp hoffman in roseland nj a lot of 
companies fell through the cracks 
stuart h bompey immigration lawyer at the new york firm of 
baer marks amp upham said large employers are complying because they 
are more sophisticated than smaller businesses and have the 
resources to efficiently keep records 
the little guy who runs the small garment shop or something 
like that probably isnt in compliance and wont be in 
