the government today urged leading corporations to 
boost imports of manufactured goods in an effort to reduce japans 
massive trade surplus 
in a meeting with representatives of 151 firms minister of 
international trade and industry hajime tamura requested the 
companies make further efforts to expand the increase of foreign 
imports said atsushi kawashima director of the import division 
of mitis international trade administration bureau 
japans trading partners have called on the country to curtail 
exports and promote imports in an effort to slash its heavy global 
trade surplus 
kawashima said imports of manufactured goods rose from 552 
billion in fiscal 1986 to 739 billion in fiscal 1987 fueled 
mainly by the rapid appreciation of the japanese yen 
since september 1985 the yen has risen by more than 100 percent 
against the us dollar the higher value of the yen has made 
japanese products more expensive overseas but has tended to 
increase the import purchasing power of japanese 
the companies should take advantage of the yens 
appreciation to the greatest extent kawashima quoted tamura as 
telling the firms representatives during the onehour meeting at 
the ministry 
according to finance ministry figures japans trade surplus 
last fiscal year totaled 7601 billion down from 8974 billion 
in fiscal 1986 the decrease was the first in six years 
kawashima said the government hopes to reduce the trade surplus 
by another 11 billion this fiscal year which ends next march 31 
he said the call for more imports also was made by ministry 
officials to 151 other firms for a total of 302 companies which 
represent the core of the japanese economy 
the corporations including big trading houses such as mitsui 
and co sumitomo corp and c itoh and co were responsible for 
60 percent of the total fiscal 1987 import figure he said the 
companies as a group increased their imports last year by 38 
percent and hope to increase them by a further 17 percent in fiscal 
1988 he said 
kawashima said tamura also requested the companies to report at 
the end of the first half of fiscal 1988 on the results of their 
import expansion programs 
