sales of new singlefamily homes rose 4 
percent in april to the highest level in a year the government 
said today 
in a joint release the departments of commerce and of housing 
and urban development said new singlefamily homes were sold at a 
seasonally adjusted annual rate of of 679000 last month up from 
the march pace of 653000 
it was the third consecutive monthly increase and the highest 
level since new homes were sold at a rate of 728000 in april 1987 
despite the recent increases sales for the first four months of 
this year are still 9 percent below the same period of 1987 when 
mortgage interest rates hit nineyear lows 
the april climb came atop a modest 12 percent rise in march and 
a whopping 114 percent rise in february however the increases 
followed three consecutive declines in november december and 
january which analysts at the time said were caused by the 
october stock market crash 
some economists had feared that the downturn in housing sales 
signaled a recession but since then the economy has proved to be 
robust and the housing sector has more than recovered 
most analysts though believe that sales levels of the last few 
months will drop by the fall as rising mortgage interest rates push 
up the monthly cost of owning a home and discourage buyers 
rates on 30year fixedrate conventional mortgages averaged 
1058 percent last week more than half a percentage point higher 
than levels in february and march 
the increase in sales of new homes was accompanied by a rise in 
prices the median or midpoint price of new homes was 110500 
in april up 33 percent from march the average price of a new 
home rose 42 percent in april 
however the increases came after two consecutive monthly price 
declines which analysts had said reflected the reentry into the 
market of firsttime home buyers who normally purchase less 
expensive homes 
sales increased in all regions of the country in april they 
were up 59 percent in the midwest 55 percent in the west 29 
percent in the south and 28 percent in the northeast 
in a separate report last week the national association of 
realtors said sales of existing homes increased 45 percent in 
april after identical increases of 25 percent in march and 
february 
